{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Zero-amount withdrawals can permanently disable emergency exits for an entire token","locations":["Staking.sol:363","Staking.sol:385","Staking.sol:487"],"claim":"`withdraw` never requires `amount > 0`, but it always updates `lastWithdrawEpochId[tokenAddress]` to the current epoch. Any user with an existing checkpoint history for a token can keep calling `withdraw(token, 0)` once per epoch and continuously refresh the global timer that `emergencyWithdraw` uses.","impact":"A single griefer can globally DoS the contract's fallback exit path for a token. If normal withdrawals ever become unavailable for that token, all stakers can remain trapped indefinitely because the 10-epoch emergency window is reset at near-zero cost.","paths":["Attacker makes an initial dust deposit in a non-stable token to create checkpoints.","Attacker later calls `withdraw(token, 0)` once per epoch.","`lastWithdrawEpochId[token]` is always recent, so `emergencyWithdraw(token)` keeps reverting for every user."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Emergency withdrawals let users recover principal while remaining counted in epoch accounting","locations":["Staking.sol:61","Staking.sol:385","Staking.sol:487","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:508","Staking.sol:558"],"claim":"`emergencyWithdraw` is gated only by the token's global `lastWithdrawEpochId`, not by any failed withdrawal attempt from the caller, and that value defaults to zero. After 10 epochs of token-wide withdrawal inactivity, a user can call `emergencyWithdraw` even when the system is otherwise healthy. The function then only zeroes `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress]` and transfers tokens out; it never updates `balanceCheckpoints` or `poolSize`, so `getEpochUserBalance` and later epoch snapshots can continue to treat the user as staked.","impact":"Users can pull out principal and still retain reward or voting weight in the staking snapshots, leading to reward theft, denominator distortion, and persistent accounting corruption for the pool. Because the gate is based on global token inactivity, this is reachable during ordinary operation for quiet pools, not only during genuine emergencies.","paths":["User stakes a non-stable token and accumulates normal checkpoints.","If that token has not had a successful withdrawal for 10 epochs, the user calls `emergencyWithdraw(token)` and receives their full principal.","Subsequent `getEpochUserBalance(user, token, epoch)` calls still return the stale checkpointed balance, and later pool snapshots can inherit the stale size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Historical pool sizes are retroactively mutable for uninitialized epochs","locations":["Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:572","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"`getEpochPoolSize` is documented as returning the amount locked during a specific epoch, but if that epoch was never initialized it falls back to the contract's current token holdings (`stableCoinBalances` for stablecoins or `token.balanceOf(address(this))` for other tokens). As a result, skipped epochs do not have immutable historical values and can report whatever the contract balance is at query time.","impact":"Any reward or accounting logic that queries past epochs without first forcing sequential initialization can read a rewritten denominator instead of the real pool size that existed in that epoch. This can misprice rewards and historical stake calculations for idle periods.","paths":["Epoch `N` passes without anyone initializing that token's pool size for the epoch.","Later deposits, withdrawals, emergency withdrawals, or direct token transfers change the contract's present balance.","A call to `getEpochPoolSize(token, N)` now returns the new balance rather than the true epoch-`N` pool size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{